title: Brexit votes in the United Kingdom by social class 2016
summary: This grouped bar chart represents 4 different Responses on X-axis for 2 groups Remain, and Leave. On the Y-axis it shows their corresponding SOME LABEL.
Response Upper Working-Class (C2) had the maximum SOME LABEL among all 2 groups, and it was for Leave. The minimum SOME LABEL was observed in Response Lower Working-Class (DE) for Remain.
In Response Upper Middle-Class (AB), Remain had the maximum SOME LABEL and it saw the lowest in Response Lower Working-Class (DE) out of all 4 Responses.
The maximum SOME LABEL for Remain that was found in Response Upper Middle-Class (AB) was 1.58 times larger than the minimum SOME LABEL observed in Response Lower Working-Class (DE).
min_summary: This grouped bar chart shows SOME LABEL on the Y-axis for 4 different Responses for 2 groups Remain, and Leave that are presented on the X-axis.
Out of all 2 groups, Leave had the highest SOME LABEL in Response Upper Working-Class (C2) and Remain had the lowest SOME LABEL in Response Lower Working-Class (DE).

max_summary: This grouped bar chart shows SOME LABEL on the Y-axis for 4 different Responses for 2 groups Remain, and Leave that are presented on the X-axis.
Out of all 2 groups, Leave had the highest SOME LABEL in Response Upper Working-Class (C2) and Remain had the lowest SOME LABEL in Response Lower Working-Class (DE).
Among all the Responses, Remain had the highest SOME LABEL in Response Upper Middle-Class (AB) and lowest SOME LABEL in Response Lower Working-Class (DE).
Response Upper Middle-Class (AB) and Lower Working-Class (DE) had the biggest gap of 21.0 between the highest and lowest SOME LABEL found for Remain.
